"The first call for every outrageous, unthinkable and unknown possibility." 

Polina Zakh (@polina__zakh), Creative Director of Russian-American studio Sila Sveta (@silasveta), walks us through what it takes to create their daring, transcendental arena-scale installations for brands like Samsung and Porsche, and 3D visuals for Billie Eilish and Drake.

Youtube link in our bio 📺

“As a kid I remember always watching my dad laying underneath a car, the feet sticking out” explains designer Anders Warming (@anders_warming_design). “I always had so much respect for the way he took care of cars.”

Follow Anders’ journey as he works to meticulously restore a car he and his father worked on together in this beautiful video hosted on our channel from our friend @alex___schiller 🟡

node.text:
Designed and realised in 1965, this villa in Rossdorf by Jan Lippert is a perfect emblem of how the Bauhaus ideal ultimately survived the early 1900s. Its clean lines and glazed facades are straight out of the Dessau school’s playbook. Although Lippert was never a student there, he did study under its director Ludwig Mies van der Rohe in the mid 1950s after he had left his native Germany for American shores.

The Rossdorf villa is a dead ringer for some of modernism’s fledgling efforts, though naturally it takes on some technological improvements from the interim years. It puts us in mind particularly of Villa Tugendhat, an early Mies van der Rohe construction in the neighbouring Czech Republic and one we’ve previously covered.

Of course there’s plenty of design commentary to be made here but more importantly, it represents a homecoming of progressive design ideals that had been so unnecessarily ostracised in the past. Jan Lippert may have remained in Illinois, had a latent appetite for the Bauhaus not reemerged across the Atlantic. In hindsight, nobody could remember just what was so threatening about houses of steel and glass.

Photos by @gregorzoyzoyla 
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
Needless to say, this reunion of Stuttgart metal at @duke_of_london’s Brentford HQ has been worth the wait. Just a week’s notice was needed to summon sixty or so of London’s Porsches to one of the city’s foremost hubs of car culture and we’re happy to report that the atmosphere has not been lost to the hiatus. 

Many of these cars represent pandemic-era projects that have gone on in the background with virtually no exposure to the broader community. While most are fairly modest about their efforts, the thrill of getting out to show off what we’ve all been up to is a hard secret to keep, second only to a calendar slowly racking up dates.

Photos and words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

Exploring the works of Japanese artist Nobuo Sekine, whose surreal sculptures explored the relationships of volume in earth and materials.

Sekine was the figurehead of a movement of sculpture in Japan called ‘mono-ha’, which was popular in the mid 1960s to 1970s and featured heavy use of materials largely thought of as industrial in type, or at least not traditionally artistic in form. Think paraffin wax, soil, and raw steel, reconfigured but not adjusted from their natural forms, recontextualised in an artistic way. Simply put, they believed they presented the world ‘as it is’.

It went against many of even the most avant-garde notions of the time in the country, but Sekine soon gained fame with the series you see above which are part of an ouevre titled ‘Phase of Nothingness’ - abstract pieces which subtly shift the earth or natural elements, making you see them in an entirely different light.

Photos via Nobuo Sekine Archive
Words by @nat_twiss for @type7

node.text:
Permanently installed in the Surrey Hills, this is Perspectives by Giles Miller (@gilesmiller). The pine cone-esque shelter is made of thousands of cedar shingles arranged in an overlapping pattern. The shelter was built in 2016 so at this stage, it’s aged to a natural colour that feels as though it’s almost simply emerged from the forest floor.

Weary-eyed and tired from the long walk up the hill, you’d be forgiven for mistaking it for something more organic.

On a closer inspection, you’ll notice the etchings in the shingles. Some are local poems, others are written by schoolchildren, the rest are contributed by regulars of the hiking trails. Miller likens them to the romantic messages carved into the bark of trees. They’re personal to the individual contributor but each are out for the world to see. Read them at your leisure but catch your breath and admire the view first, you’ll need it to get through them all.

Photos and words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
Buried into the hillside of a remote Greek island, Xerolithi House by Sinas Architects (@sinas_architects) is how you enjoy a paradise without casting a shadow across it. From a distance, you’d have a hard time knowing it was even there. The curve of the building corresponds loosely to the contour lines of the hill and the colour of the stone is virtually indistinguishable from its surroundings.

The name stems from xerolithies, the ancient stone dividing walls of Greek farmlands that remain to this day. There are many of them on this hillside and if you didn’t know better, you might have thought the house was built alongside them, long ago when the islands were first cultivated. According to the architects, it’s an under-utilised aesthetic of greek island culture that paints a broader picture than the stacked white boxes we’re used to seeing, though perhaps the fact that we’re used to seeing them says more about the observer than what there is to see.

Photos by @yiorgoskordakis 
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7
